	<abstract>
		<heading level="2">Abstract</heading>
		<paragraph>
			This poster demonstrates how to structure academic content in XML to 
			maximize accessibility for screen readers and other assistive technologies. 
			Proper semantic tagging ensures that all users can parse and comprehend 
			the data efficiently.
		</paragraph>
	</abstract>

	<content>
		<section id="introduction">
			<heading level="2">Introduction</heading>
			<paragraph>
				Traditional academic posters are highly visual, making them difficult to 
				access for visually impaired researchers. By providing a structured XML 
				alternative, we enable programmatic access to the text and data.
			</paragraph>
		</section>

		<section id="methodology">
			<heading level="2">Methodology</heading>
			<paragraph>
				We used standard XML tags, incorporating semantic elements such as 
				headings, paragraphs, and lists to establish a clear structural hierarchy.
			</paragraph>
			<list type="unordered">
				<item>Define a semantic schema that clearly separates metadata from content.</item>
				<item>Ensure every graphical element includes comprehensive alternative text (alt text).</item>
				<item>Maintain an explicit, logical reading order from top to bottom.</item>
			</list>
		</section>

		<section id="results">
			<heading level="2">Results</heading>
			<paragraph>
				Our tests showed a significant improvement in screen reader compatibility 
				compared to standard un-tagged PDF posters, as the structural semantics 
				are exposed naturally.
			</paragraph>
			<figure id="fig1">
				<image src="chart.png" alt="Bar chart showing a 100% improvement in screen reader parsing speed and user comprehension when using semantically grouped XML over un-tagged PDF."/>
				<caption>Figure 1: Screen Reader Compatibility Comparison</caption>
			</figure>
		</section>

		<section id="conclusion">
			<heading level="2">Conclusion</heading>
			<paragraph>
				Open structural standards like XML provide an effective foundation for 
				creating fully accessible digital academic resources, ensuring research 
				is available to everyone regardless of ability.
			</paragraph>
		</section>
	</content>

